WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:00.800


2
00:00:00.800 --> 00:00:04.270
Gone to be married.

3
00:00:04.270 --> 00:00:09.730
Gone to swear a peace.

4
00:00:09.730 --> 00:00:18.070
False blood to false bloodjoin'd! gone to be friends!

5
00:00:18.070 --> 00:00:26.570
Shall Lewis have Blanch,and Blanch those provinces?

6
00:00:26.570 --> 00:00:30.870
It is not so; thou hastmisspoke, misheard:

7
00:00:30.870 --> 00:00:35.600
Be well advised, tell o'erthy tale again:

8
00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:39.600
It cannot be; thou dostbut say 'tis so:

9
00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:42.070
I trust I may not trustthee; for thy word

10
00:00:42.070 --> 00:00:44.070
Is but the vain breath ofa common man:

11
00:00:44.070 --> 00:00:46.070
Believe me, I do notbelieve thee, man;

12
00:00:46.070 --> 00:00:49.800
I have a king's oath tothe contrary.

13
00:00:49.800 --> 00:00:53.770
Thou shalt be punish'd forthus frighting me,

14
00:00:53.770 --> 00:00:57.400
For I am sick and capableof fears,

15
00:00:57.400 --> 00:01:01.430
Oppress'd with wrongs andtherefore full of fears,

16
00:01:01.430 --> 00:01:06.570
A widow, husbandless,subject to fears,

17
00:01:06.570 --> 00:01:09.900
A woman, naturally born tofears;

18
00:01:09.900 --> 00:01:12.500
And though thou now confessthou didst but jest,

19
00:01:12.500 --> 00:01:14.800
With my vex'd spirits Icannot take a truce,

20
00:01:14.800 --> 00:01:19.130
But they will quake andtremble all this day.

21
00:01:19.130 --> 00:01:23.870
What dost thou mean byshaking of thy head?

22
00:01:23.870 --> 00:01:29.370
Why dost thou look sosadly on my son?

23
00:01:29.370 --> 00:01:33.930
What means that hand uponthat breast of thine?

24
00:01:33.930 --> 00:01:36.170
Why holds thine eye thatlamentable rheum,

25
00:01:36.170 --> 00:01:40.870
Like a proud river peeringo'er his bounds?

26
00:01:40.870 --> 00:01:44.930
Be these sad signsconfirmers of thy words?

27
00:01:44.930 --> 00:01:50.000
Then speak again; not allthy former tale,

28
00:01:50.000 --> 00:01:56.600
But this one word, whetherthy tale be true.

29
00:01:56.600 --> 00:01:58.770
As true as I believe youthink them false

30
00:01:58.770 --> 00:02:02.230
That give you cause toprove my saying true.

31
00:02:02.230 --> 00:02:06.030
O, if thou teach me tobelieve this sorrow,

32
00:02:06.030 --> 00:02:09.070
Teach thou this sorrow howto make me die,

33
00:02:09.070 --> 00:02:11.430
And let belief and lifeencounter so

34
00:02:11.430 --> 00:02:14.670
As doth the fury of twodesperate men

35
00:02:14.670 --> 00:02:22.470
Which in the very meetingfall and die.

36
00:02:22.470 --> 00:02:34.800
Lewis marry Blanch! O boy,then where art thou?

37
00:02:35.800 --> 00:02:41.370
France friend with England,what becomes of me?

38
00:02:41.930 --> 00:02:44.530
Fellow, be gone: I cannotbrook thy sight:

39
00:02:44.530 --> 00:02:47.430
This news hath made thee amost ugly man.

40
00:02:47.430 --> 00:02:49.000
What other harm have I,good lady, done,

41
00:02:49.000 --> 00:02:50.930
But spoke the harm that isby others done?

42
00:02:50.930 --> 00:02:52.500
Which harm within itselfso heinous is

43
00:02:52.500 --> 00:02:55.570
As it makes harmful allthat speak of it.

44
00:02:55.570 --> 00:02:58.470
I do beseech you, madam,be content.

45
00:02:58.470 --> 00:03:03.900
If thou, that bid'st me becontent, wert grim,

46
00:03:03.900 --> 00:03:07.530
Ugly and slanderous to thymother's womb,

47
00:03:07.530 --> 00:03:11.800
Full of unpleasing blotsand sightless stains,

48
00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:16.730
Lame, foolish, crooked,swart, prodigious,

49
00:03:16.730 --> 00:03:19.970
Patch'd with foul molesand eye-offending marks,

50
00:03:19.970 --> 00:03:23.900
I would not care, I thenwould be content,

51
00:03:23.900 --> 00:03:25.500
For then I should not lovethee, no, nor thou

52
00:03:25.500 --> 00:03:29.170
Become thy great birth nordeserve a crown.

53
00:03:29.170 --> 00:03:32.700
But thou art fair, and atthy birth, dear boy,

54
00:03:32.700 --> 00:03:39.300
Nature and Fortune join'dto make thee great:

55
00:03:39.300 --> 00:03:41.530
Of Nature's gifts thoumayst with lilies boast,

56
00:03:41.530 --> 00:03:47.100
And with the half-blownrose. But Fortune,

57
00:03:47.100 --> 00:03:51.400
O, She is corrupted,changed and won from thee;

58
00:03:51.400 --> 00:03:53.900
She adulterates hourlywith thine uncle John,

59
00:03:53.900 --> 00:03:57.400
And with her golden handhath pluck'd on France

60
00:03:57.400 --> 00:04:00.070
To tread down fair respectof sovereignty,

61
00:04:00.070 --> 00:04:05.300
And made his majesty thebawd to theirs.

62
00:04:05.300 --> 00:04:11.930
France is a bawd toFortune and King John,

63
00:04:11.930 --> 00:04:16.930
That strumpet Fortune,that usurping John!

64
00:04:16.930 --> 00:04:23.300
Tell me, thou fellow, isnot France forsworn?

65
00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:26.370
Envenom him with words, orget thee gone

66
00:04:26.370 --> 00:04:27.470
And leave those woes alonewhich I alone

67
00:04:27.470 --> 00:04:29.670
Am bound to under-bear.

68
00:04:29.670 --> 00:04:30.800
Pardon me, madam,

69
00:04:30.800 --> 00:04:34.270
I may not go without youto the kings.

70
00:04:35.530 --> 00:04:45.970
Thou mayst, thou shalt; Iwill not go with thee:

71
00:04:45.970 --> 00:04:49.630
I will instruct my sorrowsto be proud;

72
00:04:49.630 --> 00:04:53.930
For grief is proud andmakes his owner stoop.

73
00:04:55.830 --> 00:04:59.330
To me and to the state ofmy great grief

74
00:04:59.330 --> 00:05:04.530
Let kings assemble; for mygrief's so great

75
00:05:04.530 --> 00:05:08.070
That no supporter but thehuge firm earth

76
00:05:08.070 --> 00:05:14.970
Can hold it up: here I andsorrows sit;

77
00:05:14.970 --> 00:05:21.230
Here is my throne, bidkings come bow to it.

78
00:05:22.470 --> 00:05:25.300
'Tis true, fair daughter;and this blessed day

79
00:05:25.300 --> 00:05:27.370
Ever in France shall bekept festival:

80
00:05:27.370 --> 00:05:29.470
To solemnize this day theglorious sun

81
00:05:29.470 --> 00:05:31.130
Stays in his course andplays the alchemist,

82
00:05:31.130 --> 00:05:34.270
Turning with splendor ofhis precious eye

83
00:05:34.270 --> 00:05:37.530
The meagre cloddy earth toglittering gold:

84
00:05:37.530 --> 00:05:40.370
The yearly course thatbrings this day about

85
00:05:40.370 --> 00:05:43.130
Shall never see it but aholiday.

86
00:05:43.570 --> 00:05:46.800
A wicked day, and not aholy day!

87
00:05:46.800 --> 00:05:50.570
What hath this day deserved?what hath it done,

88
00:05:50.570 --> 00:05:52.400
That it in golden lettersshould be writ

89
00:05:52.400 --> 00:05:55.330
Among the high tides ofthe calendar?

90
00:05:55.330 --> 00:05:57.500
Nay, rather turn this dayout of the week,

91
00:05:57.500 --> 00:06:02.270
This day of shame,oppression, perjury.

92
00:06:02.270 --> 00:06:05.030
Or, if it must stand still,let wives with child

93
00:06:05.030 --> 00:06:08.200
Pray that their burthensmay not fall this day,

94
00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:11.630
Lest that their hopesprodigiously be cross'd:

95
00:06:11.630 --> 00:06:14.500
But on this day let seamenfear no wreck;

96
00:06:14.500 --> 00:06:17.670
No bargains break that arenot this day made:

97
00:06:17.670 --> 00:06:24.030
This day, all things beguncome to ill end,

98
00:06:24.770 --> 00:06:29.130
Ney, faith itself tohollow falsehood change!

99
00:06:29.130 --> 00:06:33.100
By heaven, lady, you shallhave no cause

100
00:06:33.100 --> 00:06:35.200
To curse the fairproceedings of this day:

101
00:06:35.200 --> 00:06:38.130
Have I not pawn'd to youmy majesty?

102
00:06:38.130 --> 00:06:42.770
You have beguiled me witha counterfeit

103
00:06:42.770 --> 00:06:47.400
Resembling majesty, which,being touch'd and tried,

104
00:06:47.400 --> 00:06:54.330
Proves valueless: you areforsworn, forsworn;

105
00:06:54.330 --> 00:06:58.370
You came in arms to spillmine enemies' blood,

106
00:06:58.370 --> 00:07:02.500
But now in arms youstrengthen it with yours:

107
00:07:02.500 --> 00:07:05.430
The grappling vigour andrough frown of war

108
00:07:05.430 --> 00:07:10.470
Is cold in amity andpainted peace,

109
00:07:10.470 --> 00:07:13.700
And our oppression hathmade up this deed.

110
00:07:13.700 --> 00:07:17.870
Arm, arm, you heavens,against these perjured kings!

111
00:07:17.870 --> 00:07:21.730
A widow cries; be husbandto me, heavens!

112
00:07:21.730 --> 00:07:23.570
Let not the hours of thisungodly day

113
00:07:23.570 --> 00:07:26.570
Wear out the day in peace;but, ere sunset,

114
00:07:26.570 --> 00:07:30.600
Set armed discord 'twixtthese perjured kings!

115
00:07:30.600 --> 00:07:33.570
Hear me, O, hear me!

116
00:07:33.570 --> 00:07:35.570
Lady Constance, peace!

117
00:07:35.570 --> 00:07:41.800
War! war! no peace! peaceis to me a war

118
00:07:41.800 --> 00:07:44.900
O Lymoges! O Austria! thoudost shame

119
00:07:44.900 --> 00:07:50.370
That bloody spoil: thou slave,thou wretch, thou coward!

120
00:07:50.370 --> 00:07:52.200
Thou little valiant, greatin villany!

121
00:07:52.200 --> 00:07:56.470
Thou ever strong upon thestronger side!

122
00:07:56.470 --> 00:08:01.270
Thou Fortune's championthat dost never fight

123
00:08:01.270 --> 00:08:02.700
But when her humorousladyship is by

124
00:08:02.700 --> 00:08:07.770
To teach thee safety! thouart perjured too,

125
00:08:07.770 --> 00:08:12.500
And soothest up greatness.What a fool art thou,

126
00:08:12.500 --> 00:08:15.870
A ramping fool, to bragand stamp and swear

127
00:08:15.870 --> 00:08:21.030
Upon my party! Thoucold-blooded slave,

128
00:08:21.030 --> 00:08:24.030
Hast thou not spoke likethunder on my side,

129
00:08:24.030 --> 00:08:26.600
Been sworn my champion,bidding me depend

130
00:08:26.600 --> 00:08:29.570
Upon thy fate, thyfortune and thy strength,

131
00:08:29.570 --> 00:08:32.700
And dost thou now fallover to my foes?

132
00:08:32.700 --> 00:08:36.530
Thou wear a lion's hide!doff it for shame,

133
00:08:36.530 --> 00:08:40.630
And hang a calf's-skin onthose recreant limbs.

134
00:08:40.630 --> 00:08:43.630
O, that a man should speakthose words to me!

135
00:08:43.630 --> 00:08:45.230
And hang a calf's-skin onthose recreant limbs.

136
00:08:45.230 --> 00:08:48.470
Thou darest not say so,villain, for thy life.

137
00:08:48.470 --> 00:08:51.230
And hang a calf's-skin onthose recreant limbs.

138
00:08:51.230 --> 00:08:56.130
We like not this; thoudost forget thyself.

139
00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:04.370
Here comes the holy legateof the pope.

140
00:09:04.370 --> 00:09:09.770
(♪singing)

141
00:09:14.670 --> 00:09:18.200
Hail, you anointeddeputies of heaven!

142
00:09:24.100 --> 00:09:28.930
To thee, King John, myholy errand is.

143
00:09:28.930 --> 00:09:30.670
I Pandulph, of fair Milancardinal,

144
00:09:30.670 --> 00:09:33.130
And from Pope Innocent thelegate here,

145
00:09:33.130 --> 00:09:35.270
Do in his name religiouslydemand

146
00:09:35.270 --> 00:09:39.330
Why thou against thechurch, our holy mother,

147
00:09:39.330 --> 00:09:43.930
So wilfully dost spurn;and force perforce

148
00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:47.270
Keep Stephen Langton,chosen archbishop

149
00:09:47.270 --> 00:09:50.670
Of Canterbury, from thatholy see?

150
00:09:50.670 --> 00:09:52.770
This, in our foresaid holyfather's name,

151
00:09:52.770 --> 00:09:58.930
Pope Innocent, I do demandof thee.

152
00:09:58.930 --> 00:10:01.500
What earthy name tointerrogatories

153
00:10:01.500 --> 00:10:05.700
Can task the free breathof a sacred king?

154
00:10:05.700 --> 00:10:08.670
Thou canst not, cardinal,devise a name

155
00:10:08.670 --> 00:10:11.630
So slight, unworthy andridiculous,

156
00:10:11.630 --> 00:10:16.800
To charge me to an answer,as the pope.

157
00:10:16.800 --> 00:10:19.300
Tell him this tale; andfrom the mouth of England

158
00:10:19.300 --> 00:10:21.930
Add thus much more, thatno Italian priest

159
00:10:21.930 --> 00:10:24.230
Shall tithe or toll in ourdominions;

160
00:10:24.230 --> 00:10:27.300
But as we, under God,are supreme head,

161
00:10:27.300 --> 00:10:29.270
So under Him that greatsupremacy,

162
00:10:29.270 --> 00:10:32.370
Where we do reign, we willalone uphold,

163
00:10:32.370 --> 00:10:35.870
Without the assistance ofa mortal hand:

164
00:10:35.870 --> 00:10:40.600
So tell the pope, allreverence set apart

165
00:10:40.600 --> 00:10:43.800
To him and his usurp'dauthority.

166
00:10:43.800 --> 00:10:46.500
Brother of England, youblaspheme in this.

167
00:10:46.500 --> 00:10:48.070
Though you and all thekings of Christendom

168
00:10:48.070 --> 00:10:50.800
Are led so grossly by thismeddling priest,

169
00:10:50.800 --> 00:10:54.470
Dreading the curse thatmoney may buy out;

170
00:10:54.470 --> 00:10:57.900
And by the merit of vilegold, dross, dust,

171
00:10:57.900 --> 00:10:59.870
Purchase corrupted pardonof a man,

172
00:10:59.870 --> 00:11:03.530
Who in that sale sellspardon from himself,

173
00:11:03.530 --> 00:11:05.770
Though you and all therest so grossly led

174
00:11:05.770 --> 00:11:09.930
This juggling witchcraftwith revenue cherish,

175
00:11:09.930 --> 00:11:11.370
Yet I alone, alone do meoppose

176
00:11:11.370 --> 00:11:15.600
Against the pope and counthis friends my foes.

177
00:11:17.130 --> 00:11:19.830
Then, by the lawful powerthat I have,

178
00:11:19.830 --> 00:11:25.530
Thou shalt stand cursedand excommunicate.

179
00:11:25.530 --> 00:11:27.500
And blessed shall he bethat doth revolt

180
00:11:27.500 --> 00:11:31.070
From his allegiance to anheretic;

181
00:11:31.070 --> 00:11:33.900
And meritorious shall thathand be call'd,

182
00:11:33.900 --> 00:11:36.730
Canonized and worshippedas a saint,

183
00:11:36.730 --> 00:11:41.230
That takes away by anysecret course

184
00:11:41.230 --> 00:11:45.900
Thy hateful life.

185
00:11:45.900 --> 00:11:48.530
O, lawful let it be

186
00:11:48.530 --> 00:11:52.270
That I have room with Rometo curse awhile!

187
00:11:52.270 --> 00:11:53.870
Good father cardinal, crythou amen

188
00:11:53.870 --> 00:11:56.370
To my keen curses; forwithout my wrong

189
00:11:56.370 --> 00:11:59.200
There is no tongue hathpower to curse him right.

190
00:11:59.200 --> 00:12:02.630
There's law and warrant,lady, for my curse.

191
00:12:02.630 --> 00:12:06.600
And for mine too: since lawcan do no right,

192
00:12:06.600 --> 00:12:09.770
Let it be lawful that lawbar no wrong:

193
00:12:09.770 --> 00:12:14.330
Law cannot give my childhis kingdom here,

194
00:12:14.330 --> 00:12:17.100
For he that holds hiskingdom holds the law;

195
00:12:17.100 --> 00:12:22.800
Therefore, since lawitself is perfect wrong,

196
00:12:22.800 --> 00:12:26.370
How can the law forbid mytongue to curse?

197
00:12:26.370 --> 00:12:29.430
Philip of France, on perilof a curse,

198
00:12:29.430 --> 00:12:32.600
Let go the hand of thatarch-heretic;

199
00:12:32.600 --> 00:12:34.870
And raise the power ofFrance upon his head,

200
00:12:34.870 --> 00:12:36.970
Unless he do submithimself to Rome.

201
00:12:36.970 --> 00:12:39.770
Look'st thou pale, France?do not let go thy hand.

202
00:12:39.770 --> 00:12:44.070
Philip, what say'st thouto the cardinal?

203
00:12:44.470 --> 00:12:46.970
What should he say, but asthe cardinal?

204
00:12:46.970 --> 00:12:49.530
Bethink you, father; forthe difference

205
00:12:49.530 --> 00:12:51.500
Is purchase of a heavycurse from Rome,

206
00:12:51.500 --> 00:12:53.730
Or the light loss ofEngland for a friend:

207
00:12:53.730 --> 00:12:55.100
Forego the easier.

208
00:12:55.100 --> 00:12:57.270
That's the curse of Rome.

209
00:12:57.270 --> 00:13:00.630
O Lewis, stand fast! thedevil tempts thee here

210
00:13:00.630 --> 00:13:02.670
In likeness of a newuntrimmed bride.

211
00:13:02.670 --> 00:13:04.830
The Lady Constance speaksnot from her faith,

212
00:13:04.830 --> 00:13:06.370
But from her need.

213
00:13:06.370 --> 00:13:09.830
O, if thou grant my need,

214
00:13:09.830 --> 00:13:11.830
Which only lives but bythe death of faith,

215
00:13:11.830 --> 00:13:15.200
That need must needs inferthis principle,

216
00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:18.670
That faith would liveagain by death of need.

217
00:13:18.670 --> 00:13:21.800
O then, tread down myneed, and faith mounts up;

218
00:13:21.800 --> 00:13:24.400
Keep my need up, and faithis trodden down!

219
00:13:24.400 --> 00:13:27.370
The king is moved, andanswers not to this.

220
00:13:27.370 --> 00:13:30.500
O, be removed from him,and answer well!

221
00:13:30.500 --> 00:13:33.830
I am perplex'd, and knownot what to say.

222
00:13:33.830 --> 00:13:37.570
What canst thou say butwill perplex thee more,

223
00:13:37.570 --> 00:13:42.300
If thou standexcommunicate and cursed?

224
00:13:42.300 --> 00:13:45.470
Good reverend father, makemy person yours,

225
00:13:45.470 --> 00:13:48.370
And tell me how you wouldbestow yourself.

226
00:13:48.370 --> 00:13:51.100
This royal hand and mineare newly knit,

227
00:13:51.100 --> 00:13:52.900
And the conjunction of ourinward souls

228
00:13:52.900 --> 00:13:54.530
Married in league, coupledand linked together

229
00:13:54.530 --> 00:13:58.330
With all religiousstrength of sacred vows;

230
00:13:58.330 --> 00:14:00.700
The latest breath thatgave the sound of words

231
00:14:00.700 --> 00:14:04.400
Was deep-sworn faith,peace, amity, true love

232
00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:08.400
Between our kingdoms andour royal selves,

233
00:14:08.400 --> 00:14:10.870
And even before thistruce, but new before,

234
00:14:10.870 --> 00:14:13.070
No longer than we wellcould wash our hands

235
00:14:13.070 --> 00:14:16.100
To clap this royal bargainup of peace,

236
00:14:16.100 --> 00:14:18.970
Heaven knows, they werebesmear'd and over-stain'd

237
00:14:18.970 --> 00:14:24.730
With slaughter's pencil,where revenge did paint

238
00:14:24.730 --> 00:14:28.930
The fearful difference ofincensed kings:

239
00:14:28.930 --> 00:14:34.330
And shall these hands, solately purged of blood,

240
00:14:34.330 --> 00:14:40.300
So newly sworn in faith,so strong in both,

241
00:14:40.300 --> 00:14:43.830
Unyoke this seizure andthis kind regreet?

242
00:14:43.830 --> 00:14:51.970
Play fast and loose withfaith? so jest with heaven,

243
00:14:51.970 --> 00:14:54.230
Make such unconstantchildren of ourselves,

244
00:14:54.230 --> 00:14:58.770
As now again to snatch ourpalm from palm,

245
00:14:58.770 --> 00:15:04.400
Unswear faith sworn, andon the marriage-bed

246
00:15:04.400 --> 00:15:07.800
Of smiling peace to marcha bloody host,

247
00:15:07.800 --> 00:15:10.870
And make a riot on thegentle brow

248
00:15:10.870 --> 00:15:13.870
Of true sincerity? O, holysir,

249
00:15:13.870 --> 00:15:19.370
My reverend father, let itnot be so!

250
00:15:19.370 --> 00:15:24.830
