00:30:47.870 --> 00:30:53.170
And teaches me to kill orhang myself:

503
00:30:53.170 --> 00:30:57.270
If I were mad, I shouldforget my son,

504
00:30:57.270 --> 00:31:00.300
Or madly think a babe ofclouts were he:

505
00:31:00.300 --> 00:31:05.630
I am not mad; too well,too well I feel

506
00:31:05.630 --> 00:31:09.700
The different plague ofeach calamity.

507
00:31:09.700 --> 00:31:13.170
Bind up those tresses. O,what love I note

508
00:31:13.170 --> 00:31:16.400
In the fair multitude ofthose her hairs!

509
00:31:16.400 --> 00:31:19.500
Where but by chance asilver drop hath fallen,

510
00:31:19.500 --> 00:31:23.130
Even to that drop tenthousand wiry friends

511
00:31:23.130 --> 00:31:25.530
Do glue themselves insociable grief,

512
00:31:25.530 --> 00:31:29.870
Like true, inseparable,faithful loves,

513
00:31:29.870 --> 00:31:31.830
Sticking together incalamity.

514
00:31:31.830 --> 00:31:34.630
To England, if you will.

515
00:31:34.630 --> 00:31:36.500
Bind up your hairs.

516
00:31:36.500 --> 00:31:39.430
Aye, that I will; andwherefore will I do it?

517
00:31:39.430 --> 00:31:42.530
I tore them from theirbonds and cried aloud

518
00:31:42.530 --> 00:31:44.730
'O that these hands couldso redeem my son,

519
00:31:44.730 --> 00:31:47.400
As they have given thesehairs their liberty!'

520
00:31:47.400 --> 00:31:48.970
But now I envy at theirliberty,

521
00:31:48.970 --> 00:31:51.730
And will again commit themto their bonds,

522
00:31:51.730 --> 00:31:55.170
Because my poor boy is aprisoner.

523
00:31:55.170 --> 00:31:59.770
And, father cardinal, Ihave heard you say

524
00:31:59.770 --> 00:32:04.900
That we shall see and knowour friends in heaven:

525
00:32:04.900 --> 00:32:08.700
If that be so, I shallsee my child again;

526
00:32:08.700 --> 00:32:11.930
For since the birth ofCain, the first male child,

527
00:32:11.930 --> 00:32:14.130
To him that did butyesterday suspire,

528
00:32:14.130 --> 00:32:18.270
There was not such agracious creature born.

529
00:32:18.270 --> 00:32:22.330
And now will canker-sorroweat my bud

530
00:32:22.330 --> 00:32:26.530
And chase the nativebeauty from his cheek

531
00:32:26.530 --> 00:32:31.100
And he will look as hollowas a ghost,

532
00:32:31.100 --> 00:32:35.730
As dim and meagre as anague's fit,

533
00:32:35.730 --> 00:32:42.100
And so he'll die; and,rising so again,

534
00:32:42.100 --> 00:32:47.230
When I shall meet him atthe court of heaven

535
00:32:47.230 --> 00:32:53.500
I shall not know him:therefore never, never

536
00:32:53.500 --> 00:32:56.900
Must I behold my prettyArthur more.

537
00:32:56.900 --> 00:33:01.770
You hold too heinous arespect of grief.

538
00:33:01.770 --> 00:33:04.030
He talks to me that neverhad a son.

539
00:33:04.030 --> 00:33:06.600
You are as fond of griefas of your child.

540
00:33:11.070 --> 00:33:15.270
Grief fills the room up ofmy absent child,

541
00:33:15.270 --> 00:33:19.900
Lies in his bed, walks upand down with me,

542
00:33:19.900 --> 00:33:24.370
Puts on his pretty looks,repeats his ways,

543
00:33:24.370 --> 00:33:29.830
Stuffs out his graciousgarments with his form;

544
00:33:29.830 --> 00:33:32.930
Then, have I reason to befond of grief?

545
00:33:35.630 --> 00:33:43.070
So fare you well: had yousuch a loss as I,

546
00:33:43.070 --> 00:33:47.830
I could give bettercomfort than you have.

547
00:33:47.830 --> 00:33:54.930
I will not keep this formupon my head,

548
00:33:54.930 --> 00:34:01.700
When there is suchdisorder in my wit.

549
00:34:01.700 --> 00:34:12.370
O Lord! my boy, my Arthur,my fair son!

550
00:34:12.370 --> 00:34:20.000
My life, my joy, my food,my all the world!

551
00:34:20.300 --> 00:34:27.370
My widow-comfort, and mysorrows' cure!

552
00:34:29.400 --> 00:34:34.930
I fear some outrage, andI'll follow her.

553
00:34:45.370 --> 00:34:48.270
There's nothing in thisworld can make me joy:

554
00:34:53.700 --> 00:34:57.700
Life is as tedious as atwice-told tale

555
00:34:57.700 --> 00:35:02.300
Vexing the dull ear of adrowsy man;

556
00:35:02.300 --> 00:35:05.370
And bitter shame hath spoil'dthe sweet world's taste

557
00:35:05.370 --> 00:35:10.000
That it yields nought butshame and bitterness.

558
00:35:10.000 --> 00:35:14.670
Before the curing of astrong disease,

559
00:35:14.670 --> 00:35:16.530
Even in the instant ofrepair and health,

560
00:35:16.530 --> 00:35:20.430
The fit is strongest;evils that take leave,

561
00:35:20.430 --> 00:35:26.530
On their departure most ofall show evil:

562
00:35:26.530 --> 00:35:32.500
What have you lost bylosing of this day?

563
00:35:32.500 --> 00:35:37.270
All days of glory, joy andhappiness.

564
00:35:37.270 --> 00:35:40.400
If you had won it,certainly you had.

565
00:35:42.470 --> 00:35:45.430
No, no; when Fortune meansto men most good,

566
00:35:45.430 --> 00:35:48.930
She looks upon them with athreatening eye.

567
00:35:48.930 --> 00:35:53.770
'Tis strange to think howmuch King John hath lost

568
00:35:53.770 --> 00:35:58.430
In this which he accountsso clearly won:

569
00:35:59.130 --> 00:36:02.170
Are not you grieved thatArthur is his prisoner?

570
00:36:02.170 --> 00:36:04.770
As heartily as he is gladhe hath him.

571
00:36:04.770 --> 00:36:09.930
Your mind is all asyouthful as your blood.

572
00:36:09.930 --> 00:36:11.470
Now hear me speak with aprophetic spirit;

573
00:36:11.470 --> 00:36:13.930
For even the breath ofwhat I mean to speak

574
00:36:13.930 --> 00:36:18.900
Shall blow each dust, eachstraw, each little rub,

575
00:36:18.900 --> 00:36:21.930
Out of the path thatshall directly lead

576
00:36:21.930 --> 00:36:32.900
Thy foot to England'sthrone; and therefore mark.

577
00:36:32.900 --> 00:36:36.100
John hath seized Arthur;and it cannot be

578
00:36:36.100 --> 00:36:39.330
That, whiles warm life playsin that infant's veins,

579
00:36:39.330 --> 00:36:42.400
The misplaced John shouldentertain an hour,

580
00:36:42.400 --> 00:36:46.670
One minute, nay, one quietbreath of rest.

581
00:36:46.670 --> 00:36:48.530
A sceptre snatch'd with anunruly hand

582
00:36:48.530 --> 00:36:52.170
Must be as boisterouslymaintain'd as gain'd;

583
00:36:52.170 --> 00:36:54.570
And he that stands upon aslippery place

584
00:36:54.570 --> 00:36:59.730
Makes nice of no vile holdto stay him up:

585
00:36:59.730 --> 00:37:06.030
That John may stand, thenArthur needs must fall;

586
00:37:06.330 --> 00:37:11.330
So be it, for it cannot bebut so.

587
00:37:11.330 --> 00:37:15.100
But what shall I gain byyoung Arthur's fall?

588
00:37:15.100 --> 00:37:22.570
You, in the right of LadyBlanch your wife,

589
00:37:22.570 --> 00:37:27.000
May then make all theclaim that Arthur did.

590
00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:30.930
And lose it, life and all,as Arthur did.

591
00:37:30.930 --> 00:37:35.500
How green you are andfresh in this old world!

592
00:37:35.500 --> 00:37:41.800
John lays you plots; thetimes conspire with you;

593
00:37:41.800 --> 00:37:44.030
For he that steeps hissafety in true blood

594
00:37:44.030 --> 00:37:46.830
Shall find but bloodysafety and untrue.

595
00:37:46.830 --> 00:37:50.530
This act so evilly bornshall cool the hearts

596
00:37:50.530 --> 00:37:54.000
Of all his people andfreeze up their zeal,

597
00:37:54.000 --> 00:37:56.130
That none so smalladvantage shall step forth

598
00:37:56.130 --> 00:37:58.870
To cheque his reign, butthey will cherish it;

599
00:37:58.870 --> 00:38:02.370
No natural exhalation inthe sky,

600
00:38:02.370 --> 00:38:06.100
No scope of nature, nodistemper'd day,

601
00:38:06.100 --> 00:38:07.900
No common wind, nocustomed event,

602
00:38:07.900 --> 00:38:10.630
But they will pluck awayhis natural cause

603
00:38:10.630 --> 00:38:15.570
And call them meteors,prodigies and signs,

604
00:38:15.570 --> 00:38:19.030
Abortives, presages andtongues of heaven,

605
00:38:19.030 --> 00:38:22.570
Plainly denouncingvengeance upon John.

606
00:38:22.570 --> 00:38:24.200
May be he will not touchyoung Arthur's life,

607
00:38:24.200 --> 00:38:26.970
But hold himself safe inhis prisonment.

608
00:38:26.970 --> 00:38:33.330
O, sir, when he shall hearof your approach,

609
00:38:33.330 --> 00:38:38.500
If that young Arthur benot gone already,

610
00:38:38.500 --> 00:38:45.730
Even at that news he dies;and then the hearts

611
00:38:45.730 --> 00:38:48.230
Of all his people shallrevolt from him

612
00:38:48.230 --> 00:38:53.270
And kiss the lips ofunacquainted change

613
00:38:53.270 --> 00:38:55.170
And pick strong matter ofrevolt and wrath

614
00:38:55.170 --> 00:38:58.430
Out of the bloody fingers'ends of John.

615
00:38:58.430 --> 00:39:01.570
Methinks I see this hurlyall on foot:

616
00:39:01.570 --> 00:39:03.970
And, O, what better matterbreeds for you

617
00:39:03.970 --> 00:39:07.370
Than I have named! Thebastard Faulconbridge

618
00:39:07.370 --> 00:39:11.070
Is now in England,ransacking the church,

619
00:39:11.070 --> 00:39:14.170
Offending charity: if buta dozen French

620
00:39:14.170 --> 00:39:15.870
Were there in arms, theywould be as a call

621
00:39:15.870 --> 00:39:19.500
To train ten thousandEnglish to their side,

622
00:39:19.500 --> 00:39:24.470
Or as a little snow,tumbled about,

623
00:39:24.470 --> 00:39:30.800
Anon becomes a mountain. Onoble Dauphin,

624
00:39:30.800 --> 00:39:34.370
Go with me to the king:'tis wonderful

625
00:39:34.370 --> 00:39:36.730
What may be wrought out oftheir discontent,

626
00:39:36.730 --> 00:39:40.330
Now that their souls aretopful of offence.

627
00:39:41.500 --> 00:39:47.570
For England go: I willwhet on the king.

628
00:39:49.500 --> 00:39:59.730
Strong reasons make strongactions: let us go:

629
00:39:59.730 --> 00:40:04.270
If you say ay, the kingwill not say no.

630
00:40:04.270 --> 00:40:07.200
(♪singing)

